<paragraph blockId="34.[264,1323,1836,1902]" lastBlockId="35.[264,1323,284,590]" lastPageId="35" lastPageNumber="36" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<taxonomicName authority="Smith, 1911" authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1911" box="[264,668,1836,1862]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Perigonica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fermata">
<emphasis box="[264,501,1836,1861]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Perigonica fermata</emphasis>
Smith, 
<number box="[611,668,1836,1862]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" value="1911.0">1911</number>
</taxonomicName>
was described from San Diego, California; it was diagnosed as a reddish species very similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[810,902,1876,1901]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Perigonica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tertia">
<emphasis box="[810,902,1876,1901]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">P. tertia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the 
<typeStatus box="[1083,1190,1876,1902]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">lectotype</typeStatus>
of 
<emphasis box="[1230,1319,1876,1901]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">P. t e r t i a</emphasis>
(
<collectionCode LSID="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34871" box="[272,360,284,310]" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34871" name="Smithsonian Institution, National Museum of Natural History" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">USNM</collectionCode>
) and all specimens from southern California that I have dissected, including reddish specimens that match the 
<typeStatus box="[679,741,324,350]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">types</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName box="[787,878,324,349]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Perigonica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fermata">
<emphasis box="[787,878,324,349]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">fermata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, are identical in genital morphology (
<figureCitation box="[273,363,364,390]" captionStart="FIGURES 40 – 63" captionStartId="45.[264,362,1527,1551]" captionTargetBox="[292,1293,316,1500]" captionTargetId="figure@45.[292,1294,316,1504]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="FIGURES 40 – 63. Male genitalia of the new described species and related species: 40, Protoperigea calientensis (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 41, Aseptis fanatica (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 42, Aseptis ethnica. 43, Aseptis ferruginea. 44, Aseptis torreyana (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 45, Aseptis serrula. 46, Apamea robertsoni (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 47, Apamea digitula (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 48, Apamea sordens. 49, Photedes sofiae. 50, Mammifrontia sarae (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 51, Mammifrontia rileyi (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 52, Benjaminola colorada (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 53, Perigonica tertia. 54, Perigonica fulminans. 55, Perigonica angulata. 56, Anarta fusculenta (a, valves; b, everted vesica). 57, Anarta crotchi (a, valves; b, everted vesica). 58, Anarta oaklandiae. 59, Lasionycta sala (a, valves; b, everted vesica). 60, Trichocerapoda harbisoni (a, valves; b, everted vesica). 61, Trichocerapoda comstocki. 62, Trichocerapoda oceanis (a, valves; b, everted vesica). 63. Hexorthodes nipana." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273512/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
Fig. 
<number box="[330,363,364,390]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" value="53.0">53</number>
</figureCitation>
). While the 
<typeStatus box="[513,575,364,390]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">types</typeStatus>
of 
<emphasis box="[620,711,364,389]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">P. t e r t i a</emphasis>
are pale specimens, the species shows remarkable variation in southern California, with the ground color ranging from pale yellowish gray to pinkish, rusty red, brown, and dark grayish brown. The amount of dark dusting and maculation also varies considerably. However, based on male genitalia these color forms appear to represent a single species. In contrast, 
<taxonomicName authority="Smith, 1888" authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1888" box="[847,1258,524,550]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Perigonica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulminans">
<emphasis box="[847,1103,524,549]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Perigonica fulminans</emphasis>
Smith, 
<number box="[1199,1258,524,550]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" value="1888.0">1888</number>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 40 – 63" captionStartId="45.[264,362,1527,1551]" captionTargetBox="[292,1293,316,1500]" captionTargetId="figure@45.[292,1294,316,1504]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="FIGURES 40 – 63. Male genitalia of the new described species and related species: 40, Protoperigea calientensis (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 41, Aseptis fanatica (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 42, Aseptis ethnica. 43, Aseptis ferruginea. 44, Aseptis torreyana (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 45, Aseptis serrula. 46, Apamea robertsoni (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 47, Apamea digitula (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 48, Apamea sordens. 49, Photedes sofiae. 50, Mammifrontia sarae (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 51, Mammifrontia rileyi (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 52, Benjaminola colorada (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 53, Perigonica tertia. 54, Perigonica fulminans. 55, Perigonica angulata. 56, Anarta fusculenta (a, valves; b, everted vesica). 57, Anarta crotchi (a, valves; b, everted vesica). 58, Anarta oaklandiae. 59, Lasionycta sala (a, valves; b, everted vesica). 60, Trichocerapoda harbisoni (a, valves; b, everted vesica). 61, Trichocerapoda comstocki. 62, Trichocerapoda oceanis (a, valves; b, everted vesica). 63. Hexorthodes nipana." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273512/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
Fig. 
<number box="[264,295,564,590]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" value="54.0">54</number>
</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName authority="Smith, 1890" authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1890" box="[360,645,564,590]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Perigonica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angulata">
<emphasis box="[360,493,564,589]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">P. angulata</emphasis>
Smith, 
<number box="[586,645,564,590]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" value="1890.0">1890</number>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[660,745,564,590]" captionStart="FIGURES 40 – 63" captionStartId="45.[264,362,1527,1551]" captionTargetBox="[292,1293,316,1500]" captionTargetId="figure@45.[292,1294,316,1504]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="FIGURES 40 – 63. Male genitalia of the new described species and related species: 40, Protoperigea calientensis (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 41, Aseptis fanatica (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 42, Aseptis ethnica. 43, Aseptis ferruginea. 44, Aseptis torreyana (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 45, Aseptis serrula. 46, Apamea robertsoni (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 47, Apamea digitula (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 48, Apamea sordens. 49, Photedes sofiae. 50, Mammifrontia sarae (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 51, Mammifrontia rileyi (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 52, Benjaminola colorada (a, valve; b, everted vesica). 53, Perigonica tertia. 54, Perigonica fulminans. 55, Perigonica angulata. 56, Anarta fusculenta (a, valves; b, everted vesica). 57, Anarta crotchi (a, valves; b, everted vesica). 58, Anarta oaklandiae. 59, Lasionycta sala (a, valves; b, everted vesica). 60, Trichocerapoda harbisoni (a, valves; b, everted vesica). 61, Trichocerapoda comstocki. 62, Trichocerapoda oceanis (a, valves; b, everted vesica). 63. Hexorthodes nipana." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273512/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
Fig. 
<number box="[715,745,564,590]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" value="55.0">55</number>
</figureCitation>
) have distinctive valve morphologies.
</paragraph>
